ed-to-ken-miles-son-peter.php|title='Ford v. Ferrari': What Happened to Ken Miles' Son, Peter?|first=Dustin|last=Rowles|date=2019-11-16|accessdate=2019-11-25|df=dmy-all}}</ref> was almost 15. A few months after Ken's death, Peter went to work for Ken's friend Dick Troutman at the Troutman and Barnes custom car shop in Culver City, CA. Peter stayed at the workshop for four years. In 1986, Peter joined [[PPI Motorsports|Precision Performance Inc.]] (PPI), starting as a fabricator and then a mechanic before becoming the crew chief. Peter was the crew chief for [[Ivan Stewart]] when Stewart won the 1991 [[Mint 400|Nissan 400]] in Nevada.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1991-06-06-sp-55-story.html|title=MOTOR RACING : Miles Has Taken His Own Route to Father's Sport|date=1991-06-06|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-16}}</ref> In a 2019 interview with Le Mans, Peter revealed that the last time he went to Le Mans was in 1965 with his father Ken, and he has not returned since.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lemans.org/app_dev.php/en/news/le-mans-66-ford-v-ferrari-peter-miles-talks-about-his-father-ken-miles/52849|title=\"Le Mans 66\" (\"Ford v Ferrari\") \u2013 Peter Miles talks about his father, Ken Miles|website=lemans.org|language=fr|access-date=2019-11-16}}</ref>\n\nPeter is currently an executive administrator of a vintage car collection belonging to [[William E. Connor II]]., believed to be valued at over $80 million, which included a [[Ferrari 250 GTO]], considered by respected Ferrari historian Marcel Massini as the best example of all 36 built.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://argonautnews.com/gentlemen-start-your-engines/|title=Gentlemen, start your engines|website=The Argonaut Newsweekly|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/2000/12/11/1214vehiclesate.html|title=Marcel Massini, Ferrari Historian|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2019-12-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.barchetta.cc/english/All.Ferraris/Detail/4293GT.250GTO.htm|title=250 GTO s/n 4293GT|website=www.barchetta.cc|access-date=2019-12-04}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nMiles is portrayed by [[Christian Bale]] in the 2019 film ''[[Ford v Ferrari]]'' (released under the title ''Le Mans '66'' in some parts of Europe)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/james-mangold-next-film-ford-ferrari-logan-1202687686/ |title=James Mangold to Direct Ford vs. Ferrari Film as 'Logan' Follow-Up |publisher=variety.com |accessdate=5 February 2018}}</ref> Miles' wife Mollie and his son Peter are portrayed by [[Caitriona Balfe]] and [[Noah Jupe]], respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/outlander-a-quiet-place-stars-join-ford-ferrari-movie-1114517 |title='Outlander' Star Caitriona Balfe, 'Quiet Place' Breakout Noah Jupe Join Ford vs. Ferrari Movie |publisher=hollywoodreporter.com |accessdate=23 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/ford-v-ferrari-trailer-matt-damon-christian-bale-design-race-car-1214837|title='Ford v. Ferrari' Trailer: Matt Damon, Christian Bale Team Up to Design Race Car|publisher=hollywoodreporter.com |date=2 June 2019 |accessdate=3 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.saac.com Shelby American Automobile Club World Registry of Cobras & GT40s]\n* {{findagrave|92639918}}\n\n{{24 Hours of Daytona winners}}\n{{12 Hours of Sebring winners}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Miles, Ken}}\n[[Category:1918 births]]\n[[Category:1966 deaths]]\n[[Category:English expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:English racing drivers]]\n[[Category:Racing drivers killed while racing]]\n[[Category:Sports deaths in California]]\n[[Category:Accidental deaths in California]]\n[[Category:24 Hours of Le Mans drivers]]\n[[Category:24 Hours of Daytona drivers]]\n[[Category:World Sportscar Championship drivers]]\n[[Category:12 Hours of Sebring drivers]]\n", "name_user": "John rike", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eDeath:Yes)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ken_Miles"}
{"title_page": "2000 Arizona Diamondbacks season", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2013}}\n{{Infobox MLB yearly\n| name = Arizona Diamondbacks\n| season = 2000\n| image =\n| misc = \n| logo = ARI 1998-2006.PNG\n| current league = National League\n| y1 =  1998\n| division = [[National League West|Western Division]]\n| y2 =  1998\n| Uniform logo =\n| ballpark = [[Bank One Ballpark]]\n| y4 = 1998\n| city = [[Phoenix, Arizona]]\n| y5 = 1998\n| record = 85\u201377 (.525)\n| divisional place = 3rd\n| owners = [[Ken Kendrick]]<br>[[Jerry Colangelo]]\n| general managers = [[Joe Garagiola Jr.]]\n| managers = [[Buck Showalter]]\n| television = [[Fox Sports Net|FSN Arizona]]<br>[[KTVK]] (3TV)<br>([[Thom Brennaman]], [[Greg Schulte]], [[Bob Brenly]], [[Joe Garagiola]])\n| radio =  [[KTAR (AM)|KTAR]] (620 AM)<br>([[Thom Brennaman]], [[Rod Allen]], [[Greg Schulte]])<br>[[KSUN]] (Spanish)<br>(Jose Tolentino, Ivan Lara)\n| espntn = ari\n| brtn = ARI\n|}}\nThe '''2000 [[Arizona Diamondbacks]]''' looked to improve on their 1999 season, in which they won 100 games in just their 2nd season. They looked to contend in what was a strong [[National League]] [[National League West|West Division]]. They finished the season with a record of 85-77, good enough for third place in the division.\n\n==Offseason==\n*November 15, 1999: [[Ken Huckaby]] was signed as a Free Agent with the Arizona Diamondbacks.<ref>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/h/huckake01.shtml Ken Huckaby Statistics - Baseball-Reference.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n*November 22, 1999: Ernie Young was released by the Arizona Diamondbacks.<ref>https://www.baseball-reference.com/y/younger02.shtml</ref>\n*December 15, 1999: Dante Powell was traded by the Arizona Diamondbacks to the St. Louis Cardinals for Luis Ordaz.<ref>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/p/powelda01.shtml Dante Powell Statistics - Baseball-Reference.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n*March 20, 2000: [[Craig Counsell]] was signed as a Free Agent with the Arizona Diamondbacks.<ref>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/c/counscr01.shtml Craig Counsell Statistics - Baseball-Reference.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==Regular season==\nRandy Johnson tied a modern record with six victories in April 2000.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{Cite web |url=http://www.baseballlibrary.com/ballplayers/player.php?name=Randy_Johnson_1963 |title=The Ballplayers - Randy Johnson {{!}} BaseballLibrary.com<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=August 12, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080209050200/http://www.baseballlibrary.com/ballplayers/player.php?name=Randy_Johnson_1963 |archive-date=February 9, 2008 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> He would lead the league in strikeouts with 347 and in winning percentage. Johnson won his third Cy Young Award, and became the third National League pitcher to win the trophy in consecutive seasons.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> Johnson recorded his 3000th strikeout on September 10, 2000, as he whiffed Florida Marlins' third baseman Mike Lowell.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\n===Opening Day starters===\n* Jay Bell\n* Erubiel Durazo\n* Steve Finley\n* Luis Gonzalez\n* Lenny Harris\n* Randy Johnson\n* Travis Lee\n* Damian Miller\n* Tony Womack\n\n===Notable transactions===\n*June 2, 2000: Bill Pulsipher was traded by the New York Mets to the Arizona Diamondbacks for Lenny Harris.<ref>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/p/pulsibi01.shtml Bill Pulsipher Statistics - Baseball-Reference.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n*June 5, 2000: Brandon Webb was drafted by the Arizona Diamondbacks in the 8th round of the 2000 amateur draft. Player signed June 6, 2000.<ref>https://www.baseball-reference.com/w/webbbr01.shtml</ref>\n* July 26, 2000: Curt Schilling was traded by the Philadelphia Phillies to the Arizona Diamondbacks for Omar Daal, Nelson Figueroa, Travis Lee, and Vicente Padilla.\n\n===Season standings===\n{{2000 NL West standings|highlight=Arizona Diamondbacks}